@jimcramer @carlquintanilla @davidfaber Interest rates don’t have to increase a lot to make Italy’s debt unsustainable. The average cost of debt stands at about 3.1%. The seven-year yield has increased to 2.94% from 1.12% four weeks ago.

An increase would be disastrous for public finances, even in the absence of additional spending. If the cost of funds faced by the Italian government were to rise to 3.5% from 3.1%, the debt ratio would be on an upward trajectory. The International Monetary Fund tends
to consider a country’s debts sustainable if the ratio is declining over a forecast horizon. A move to 4% would leave the number about 12 percentage points higher than it would have otherwise been.
